ion of the skill teaches the new surface automatically.\n109\t3. The skill is **workflow-shaped**: it presents commands as \"if you want\n110\t   to do X → run `entire …`\" pairs, not as a catalog. It maps the\n111\t   subcommands discovered in step 2 onto a small fixed set of user goals\n112\t   (set up, see what happened, find prior work, understand a change,\n113\t   undo / recover, summarize, share / collaborate, troubleshoot,\n114\t   advanced). Subcommands that do not match any goal are listed as\n115\t   \"Other commands available in your CLI: …\" so nothing is silently\n116\t   hidden, but they are not promoted.\n117\t4. The skill **never teaches an experimental command without flagging\n118\t   it**. After enumerating subcommands, it inspects each one's help text\n119\t   for the markers `experimental`, `beta`, `alpha`, `preview`, or\n120\t   `labs` (case-insensitive, whole-word) and tags any matching command\n121\t   `(experimental)` in its workflow lines. If the CLI ever introduces a\n122\t   top-level group named `labs` (it does not today), the same rule\n123\t   applies: list its members under \"Other commands\" with the\n124\t   `(experimental)` tag rather than under the main workflow goals.\n125\t5. The skill detects the user's current state (`entire` installed?\n126\t   inside a git repo? `entire enable` run in this repo? supported\n127\t   agents installed? authenticated for cloud search? any usable local\n128\t   or remote history available?) and adapts its branch accordingly —\n129\t   it does not lecture a user who is already set up, and it does not\n130\t   skip past setup for a user who has not run `entire enable`.\n131\t6. When usable history exists, the skill demos exactly one concrete\n132\t   result against the user's repo using a CLI command that exists in\n133\t   their installed help surface. When history does not exist yet, the\n134\t   skill ends with the exact next capture step needed to create that\n135\t   first result.\n136\t7. The skill mentions each focused skill (`search`, `explain`,\n137\t   `what-happened`, `session-handoff`, `session-to-skill`) at most\n138\t   once, as a \"deeper drill-down\" hint inline with the matching\n139\t   workflow goal — not as the primary content. Removing all skill\n140\t   mentions must still leave the response useful on its own.\n141\t8. Update `README.md` so the new skill appears in Quick Start, the\n142\t   \"What skills help agents do\" table, and the \"Included skills\" list.\n143\t   While touching that section, fix the current README drift by\n144\t   ensuring the already-shipped `session-to-skill` skill is listed\n145\t   there too.\n146\t9. Ship the skill through every packaging surface that actually\n147\t   versions this repo today: the six versioned manifests plus the\n148\t   pinned tag in `.opencode/INSTALL.md`, then verify discovery with the\n149\t   validation command in `CONTRIBUTING.md`.\n150\t\n151\t## Non-Goals\n152\t\n153\t- No changes to the `entire` CLI itself. This plan lives entirely in the\n154\t  `entireio/skills` repo.\n155\t- Not a replacement for `docs.entire.io` — the skill links to docs for depth,\n156\t  it does not duplicate them.\n157\t- Not a setup automation. The skill instructs the user to run `entire enable`,\n158\t  `entire login`, and `entire agent add <name>` interactively; it does not run\n159\t  those for them, because they need the user's choices (telemetry, agent\n160\t  selection, checkpoint remote).\n161\t- No new CLI subcommand, no new MCP tool, no plugin manifest changes beyond\n162\t  what skill discovery requires.\n163\t- Not a session-recap skill. If the user wants to summarize a past session,\n164\t  they want `session-handoff` or `session-to-skill`; this skill points there\n165\t  rather than reimplementing it.\n166\t- Not a video/asset deliverable. Adding a recording to the README is out of\n167\t  scope for this PR; the existing four skills have recordings, so a follow-up\n168\t  recording can be added later without changing the skill itself.\n169\t\n170\t## Proposal\n171\t\n172\t### Skill name and location\n173\t\n174\t- Path: `skills/getting-started/SKILL.md`\n175\t- Skill `name`: `getting-started`\n176\t- Invoked as `/getting-started` (Claude Code), and as `entire:getting-started`\n177\t  in cross-agent contexts where the plugin namespace is exposed.\n178\t\n179\t`getting-started` was chosen over `tour`, `intro`, or `entire-tour` because it\n180\tmatches the prompts a new user actually types, is the conventional name for\n181\tthis category of skill across plugins, and avoids colliding with this repo's\n182\tearlier `code-tour` / `project-overview` concept, which was about onboarding to\n183\tan unfamiliar repository rather than onboarding to Entire itself.\n184\t\n185\t### Frontmatter\n186\t\n187\t```yaml\n188\t---\n189\tname: getting-started\n190\tdescription: >\n191\t  Use when the user is new to Entire and wants an overview of what the CLI\n192\t  does, an interactive tour of the main workflows, or a guided first run.\n193\t  Triggers on phrases like \"I'm new to Entire\", \"give me a tour\", \"teach me\n194\t  Entire\", \"what can Entire do\", \"getting started\", \"show me how this works\",\n195\t  \"intro to Entire\", \"how do I use entire\", and \"where do I start\".\n196\t---\n197\t```\n198\t\n199\tThe description is intentionally trigger-heavy because these phrases are how\n200\tnew users actually ask, and because the existing five skills are all\n201\ttask-shaped and will not match intro phrasing.\n202\t\n203\t### Response header\n204\t\n205\tFollowing the convention used by every other skill in this repo (`Entire\n206\tSearch:`, `Entire Explain:`, `Entire What Happened:`, `Entire Session\n207\tHandoff:`, `Entire Session To Skill:`), this skill begins its first successful\n208\tresponse with:\n209\t\n210\t```\n211\tEntire Getting Started:\n212\t```\n213\t\n214\tfollowed by a blank line, then the content. `Entire Tour:` was rejected because\n215\tit reads like a continuation of the older `code-tour` repo-overview work; the\n216\theader should line up with the actual skill name. Header rules match the\n217\texisting skills:\n218\t\n219\t- Apply the header to the first response of the invocation only.\n220\t- Do not include the header on early-exit error responses (CLI not installed,\n221\t  not a git repo, etc.).\n222\t- Do not re-print the header on follow-up turns within the same invocation.\n223\t\n224\t### Workflow\n225\t\n226\tThe skill body is structured as a preflight → state-detection →\n227\t**discovery from `entire --help`** → workflow-shaped tour → live-demo flow.\n228\tEach section names exact commands so the agent does not improvise, and the\n229\tdiscovery step is what makes the skill self-updating.\n230\t\n231\t**1. Preflight and detect state.** Run the first set in parallel and do not\n232\tshow raw output:\n233\t\n234\t```bash\n235\tgit rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree\n236\tentire version\n237\tentire status --json\n238\tentire auth status\n239\tentire session current --json\n240\t```\n241\t\n242\tIf `entire status --json` says Entire is enabled, gather the local-history\n243\tprobes in parallel:\n244\t\n245\t```bash\n246\tentire checkpoint list --no-pager\n247\tentire dispatch --local --all-branches --since 30d\n248\t```\n249\t\n250\tUse those commands to derive state with these rules:\n251\t\n252\t- `git rev-parse` fails → tell the user Entire works inside a git repository,\n253\t  and stop without the header.\n254\t- `entire version` fails / command not found → tell the user how to install\n255\t  the CLI (link to `https://docs.entire.io/cli/install`), and stop without the\n256\t  header.\n257\t- `entire status --json` says `enabled: false` → enter the **Setup tour**\n258\t  branch.\n259\t- `entire status --json` says `enabled: true` and `agents: []` → enter the\n260\t  **Agent install** branch.\n261\t- `entire status --json` says enabled and agents are installed, but the repo has\n262\t  no usable history yet → enter the **First-capture tour** branch.\n263\t- `entire status --json` says enabled and agents are installed, and the repo has\n264\t  usable history → enter the **Workflow tour** branch.\n265\t\n266\t`usable history` means any one of:\n267\t\n268\t- `entire checkpoint list --no-pager` shows at least one checkpoint on the\n269\t  current branch (i.e. its output does not include the literal line\n270\t  `No checkpoints found on this branch.`),\n271\t- `entire session current --json` returns a session object whose `checkpoints`\n272\t  field (or equivalent count) is `> 0`,\n273\t- `entire dispatch --local --all-branches --since 30d` exits 0 and prints a\n274\t  Markdown summary that contains at least one section heading\n275\t  (e.g. a `## ` line) — i.e. it is not just a \"no recent activity\" stub.\n276\t\n277\tDo **not** use `entire checkpoint list` as the sole gate. It is branch-local.\n278\tIn this repo right now, `entire checkpoint list --no-pager` on\n279\t`learn-entire-cli` prints `No checkpoints found on this branch` even though\n280\t`entire dispatch --local --all-branches --since 30d` returns a real Markdown\n281\treport summarizing recent Entire history across local branches. The skill\n282\tmust treat that combination as the **Workflow tour** state, not the\n283\t**First-capture tour** state.\n284\t\n285\t**2. Discover the live CLI surface (every successful invocation).** Before\n286\tpresenting any workflow content, run:\n287\t\n288\t```bash\n289\tentire --help\n290\t```\n291\t\n292\tParse the `Available Commands:` block: every line in that block has the\n293\tshape `^  <name>\\s{2,}<short description>$`. The list of names produced by\n294\tthat parse is the set of **top-level command groups** the skill is allowed\n295\tto teach. For each name in that list, also run:\n296\t\n297\t```bash\n298\tentire help <name>\n299\t```\n300\t\n301\t(or `entire <name> --help` if `entire help` fails) so the skill has the\n302\tshort description, longer help text, and any subcommands. Parse each\n303\ttop-level help page's own `Available Commands:` block the same way so the\n304\tskill can promote concrete command paths like `agent add`,\n305\t`session current`, `session list`, `checkpoint explain`, and\n306\t`checkpoint search` instead of only opaque group names. Then, for each\n307\texplicit subcommand path discovered from those pages that may be rendered\n308\tto the user, also run that leaf help page (`entire <name> <subcommand>\n309\t--help`, or `entire help <name> <subcommand>` if supported) so the skill\n310\thas the exact help text for the concrete command path it is about to\n311\tteach. Fan out these independent help lookups in parallel rather than\n312\tsequentially so the skill does not turn the tour into a slow help crawl.\n313\tThe allowed\n314\trendered command surface for one invocation is therefore:\n315\t\n316\t- every top-level command listed in `entire --help`, plus\n317\t- every explicit subcommand path listed in the help output of those\n318\t  top-level commands.\n319\t\n320\tCache these outputs for the duration of one invocation only — the next\n321\tinvocation re-reads them so a CLI upgrade between invocations is picked up\n322\tautomatically.\n323\t\n324\tThe skill then derives, in memory, a structured map shaped roughly like:\n325\t\n326\t```text\n327\t{ path, summary, helpText, parent, subcommands, requiresLogin, isExperimental, goals }\n328\t```\n329\t\n330\t`requiresLogin` is true if the help text for that exact rendered command\n331\tpath says authentication is required (for example `entire checkpoint search\n332\t--help` currently says `Requires authentication via 'entire login'`).\n333\tThis check must use the leaf command's own help text, not only its parent\n334\tgroup help page; `entire checkpoint --help` does not carry the auth\n335\trequirement for `entire checkpoint search`.\n336\tRendered workflow lines and \"Other commands available in your CLI\" entries\n337\tappend `(login required)` when this is true, so logged-out users can see\n338\twhich workflows are cloud-backed before they try them.\n339\t\n340\t`isExperimental` is true if `helpText` for that exact rendered command path\n341\tcontains a whole-word\n342\tcase-insensitive match for `experimental`, `beta`, `alpha`, `preview`,\n343\tor `labs`. `goals` is a small set of fixed labels the skill assigns by\n344\tmatching the command path and short description against the table below;\n345\tthe names on the right are the labels used in the rendered tour, not the\n346\tliteral command names.\n347\t\n348\t| If the CLI exposes…              | the skill places it under goal… |\n349\t| --------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |\n350\t| `enable`, `disable`, `agent add`, `agent list`, `login`, `logout`, `auth`, `configure` | Set up |\n351\t| `status`, `session current`, `session list`, `session info`, `activity` | See what's going on |\n352\t| `checkpoint search` | Find prior work |\n353\t| `checkpoint explain`, `checkpoint list` | Understand a change |\n354\t| `checkpoint rewind`, `clean` | Undo / recover |\n355\t| `dispatch` | Summarize / share |\n356\t| `doctor` | Troubleshoot |\n357\t| anything else (including unknown names from a future release) | Other commands available in your CLI |\n358\t\n359\tThe mapping table itself is part of the skill body. The skill\n360\t**never invents** command paths that are not in the discovered help\n361\tsurface; if a goal has no matching command path in this CLI version,\n362\tthat goal is omitted from the rendered tour rather than filled with a\n363\tguess. If a discovered command path does not match any goal (e.g. a\n364\thypothetical future top-level `entire trace` or a nested\n365\t`entire doctor trace` that the workflow table does not promote), the\n366\tskill lists it under \"Other commands available in your CLI\" with its\n367\tshort description verbatim and no extra wording.\n368\t\n369\t**3. Setup tour branch.** Tell the user, in 5–8 lines:\n370\t- what `entire enable` does (turns on session capture and checkpointing\n371\t  in this repo),\n372\t- to run it now: `entire enable`,\n373\t- to log in if they want cloud search: `entire login`,\n374\t- that they will be asked which agent to install hooks for, and the\n375\t  next step is `entire agent add <agent-name>`,\n376\t- then re-invoke this skill so the tour can continue with real state.\n377\t\n378\tDo not run `entire enable` for them — the command is interactive and\n379\tasks about telemetry, agent selection, and checkpoint remote. Names\n380\tused here (`enable`, `login`, `agent add`) are confirmed against the\n381\tdiscovery output before being printed; if any of them is missing from\n382\tthe live `entire --help` (e.g. on a stripped-down distribution), drop\n383\tthe missing line from this branch instead of printing a dead\n384\tinstruction.\n385\t\n386\t**4. Agent install branch.** Detect the user's agent from environment\n387\tif possible (`CLAUDE_CODE`, `CODEX_*`, `CURSOR_*`, `OPENCODE_*`, etc.;\n388\tfall back to asking). Tell the user to run `entire agent add\n389\t<agent-name>` and explain that this installs the hooks that capture\n390\tsessions and create checkpoints on commit. Mention `entire agent list`\n391\tto see what is supported. (`agent` and its `add` / `list` subcommands\n392\tmust appear in the discovered surface; if they do not, fall back to\n393\t\"Run `entire help` to see how to install agent hooks in your version.\")\n394\t\n395\t**5. First-capture tour branch.** Entire is enabled and a supported\n396\tagent is installed, but there is not enough captured history yet to\n397\tdemo the workflows concretely. Tell the user that checkpoints are\n398\tcreated automatically when their agent runs and commits, and that to\n399\tsee the system work end-to-end they should:\n400\t- run a small task with their agent (any task, even \"say hello in a\n401\t  comment\"),\n402\t- commit the change,\n403\t- optionally run `entire login` if they want cloud search as part of\n404\t  the tour,\n405\t- come back and re-invoke this skill — there will be captured history\n406\t  to demo.\n407\t\n408\tDo not fabricate a checkpoint or run a placeholder task on the user's\n409\tbehalf.\n410\t\n411\t**6. Workflow tour branch (the main path).** Render the goals → command\n412\trecipe. The lines below are the **template**; the actual rendered text\n413\tis built from the discovery output, so any goal whose required command\n414\tpath is absent is dropped, any command path marked `requiresLogin`\n415\tgets a `(login required)` suffix, and any command marked\n416\t`isExperimental` gets an `(experimental)` suffix. The deeper-drill-down skill names in\n417\tparentheses are mentioned at most once each and only on the line where\n418\tthe workflow already exists in the CLI:\n419\t\n420\t```text\n421\tHere is what your installed Entire CLI can do (entire <CLI version>):\n422\t\n423\t- Set up                  →  entire enable / entire agent add <name> / entire login\n424\t- See what's going on     →  entire status / entire session current / entire session list / entire activity\n425\t- Find prior work         →  entire checkpoint search \"<query>\" (login required)      (deeper: /search)\n426\t- Understand a change     →  entire checkpoint explain <id|sha>      (deeper: /explain, /what-happened)\n427\t- Undo / recover          →  entire checkpoint rewind  /  entire clean\n428\t- Summarize / share       →  entire dispatch --since 7d              (deeper: /session-handoff)\n429\t- Troubleshoot            →  entire doctor\n430\t\n431\tOther commands available in your CLI:\n432\t- <name>: <short description verbatim from `entire --help`>\n433\t- ...\n434\t```\n435\t\n436\tThe skill prefers the canonical command spellings advertised in\n437\t`entire --help`. `entire search` exists today as a hidden alias of\n438\t`entire checkpoint search`; the rendered tour uses\n439\t`entire checkpoint search` because that is the form the live help\n440\tactually advertises. If a future CLI release promotes `search` to a\n441\ttop-level command (it would then appear in `Available Commands`), the\n442\tdiscovery step picks that up and the rendered line uses the shorter\n443\tform on its own. Likewise, auth-gated commands are tagged from the live\n444\thelp text for that exact command path, not from a hardcoded list.\n445\t\n446\tThen **demo exactly one** concrete Entire result, using a valid command\n447\tpath in this order. Each candidate is only attempted if its command was\n448\tpresent in the discovery output:\n449\t\n450\t- If `entire auth status` says the user is logged in **and**\n451\t  `git config --get remote.origin.url` resolves to a GitHub repo slug,\n452\t  try a repo-scoped search first:\n453\t\n454\t```bash\n455\tentire checkpoint search \"<current-repo-basename>\" --repo <owner/name> --json --limit 3\n456\t```\n457\t\n458\t  If that search returns at least one hit, summarize the top hit as\n459\t  the demo and point out that `/search` is the skill for deeper use.\n460\t  If it returns zero hits, do **not** show an empty result; fall\n461\t  through to the local checkpoint / dispatch demo path below so the\n462\t  tour still ends with evidence from this repo.\n463\t\n464\t- Otherwise, if `entire checkpoint list --no-pager` shows at least one\n465\t  checkpoint on the current branch, expand the newest checkpoint with\n466\t  the current command spelling:\n467\t\n468\t```bash\n469\tentire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --short --no-pager\n470\t```\n471\t\n472\t  Summarize that checkpoint as the demo and point out that `/explain`\n473\t  and `/what-happened` drill into the same captured history more\n474\t  precisely.\n475\t\n476\t- Otherwise, use the local cross-branch summary command:\n477\t\n478\t```bash\n479\tentire dispatch --local --all-branches --since 30d\n480\t```\n481\t\n482\t  Summarize one recent thread of work and frame it as \"this is the\n483\t  captured history the deeper workflows search and explain.\"\n484\t\n485\tEnd with a one-liner that points at `docs.entire.io/cli` for deeper\n486\tdocs and mentions that the focused skills (`/search`, `/explain`,\n487\t`/what-happened`, `/session-handoff`, `/session-to-skill`) drill into\n488\tthe same workflows above when the user wants more than the CLI\n489\trecipes.\n490\t\n491\t### Failure modes\n492\t\n493\tThe skill must distinguish and report each of these states explicitly:\n494\t\n495\t- `entire` not installed → \"The Entire CLI is required but not installed.\n496\t  Install it from https://docs.entire.io/cli/install and try again.\"\n497\t  No header.\n498\t- Current directory is not a git repo → \"Entire works inside a git\n499\t  repository. Run `git init` first or `cd` into one, then re-invoke this\n500\t  skill.\" No header.\n501\t- `entire status` works but says disabled → enter the Setup tour branch\n502\t  (this is success, header applies).\n503\t- `entire login` required for cloud search → mention it in the tour but do\n504\t  not block local-only tours on it. Search is auth-gated; `status`,\n505\t  `session current`, `checkpoint list`, and `dispatch --local` still give the\n506\t  user value without logging in.\n507\t- Any other CLI error → report the exact error in one short excerpt and\n508\t  suggest re-running with `--help` or filing a `doctor` report\n509\t  (`entire doctor`). No header.\n510\t\n511\t### Files changed in this PR\n512\t\n513\tThis entire change ships in a single PR with these files:\n514\t\n515\t1. `skills/getting-started/SKILL.md` — new file. The body must contain\n516\t   (a) the trigger-heavy frontmatter, (b) the response-header rule,\n517\t   (c) the preflight + state-detection commands, (d) the live-help\n518\t   discovery procedure including the `Available Commands:` parser\n519\t   contract and the experimental-tag rule, (e) the goal-mapping table,\n520\t   (f) the four state branches, (g) the demo-fallback chain, and\n521\t   (h) the failure-mode handling — i.e. every behavior described in\n522\t   this Plan's Workflow section. No discovery output is hardcoded into\n523\t   the skill text.\n524\t2. `README.md` — add a Quick Start example prompt for the guided tour, add a\n525\t   \"Get a guided tour of Entire\" row to the \"What skills help agents do\"\n526\t   table, add a `### \\`getting-started\\`` entry under \"Included skills\", and\n527\t   restore/keep the `session-to-skill` entry so the public list matches the\n528\t   shipped tree.\n529\t3. `package.json`, `gemini-extension.json`,\n530\t   `.claude-plugin/plugin.json`, `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json`,\n531\t   `.codex-plugin/plugin.json`, `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json`\n532\t   — bump `version` from `0.3.0` to `0.4.0` (minor bump for a new user-facing\n533\t   skill). For `.claude-plugin/marketplace.json` the version field lives at\n534\t   `plugins[0].version`; for the other five it lives at the document root.\n535\t4. `.opencode/INSTALL.md` — update the pinned git tag example from `v0.3.0`\n536\t   to `v0.4.0` so the install doc matches the shipped release.\n537\t\n538\tNo new dependencies. No CLI changes. No new manifest fields. No edit to\n539\t`.agents/plugins/marketplace.json` because that file does not carry a\n540\t`version` field — it only declares plugin source, policy, and category, and\n541\tthose are unchanged by this PR. No edit to `.opencode/plugins/entire.js`\n542\tbecause the shim already auto-registers the entire `skills/` directory\n543\trather than enumerating a hardcoded skill list (verified by reading the\n544\tfile: it walks `path.resolve(__dirname, '../../skills')` and pushes that\n545\tdirectory into `config.skills.paths`).\n546\t\n547\t### Validation in this PR\n548\t\n549\tBefore opening the PR, run the commands listed in `CONTRIBUTING.md` verbatim\n550\tso we exercise the same contract every contributor uses:\n551\t\n552\t```bash\n553\tnpx -y skills@latest add . --list --yes\n554\tnode -e 'for (const f of [\"package.json\",\"gemini-extension.json\",\".codex-plugin/plugin.json\",\".claude-plugin/plugin.json\",\".cursor-plugin/plugin.json\",\".agents/plugins/marketplace.json\"]) JSON.parse(require(\"fs\").readFileSync(f, \"utf8\"))'\n555\t```\n556\t\n557\tThe first command must list `getting-started` alongside the other five\n558\tskills. The second must exit cleanly. Then, because this PR also edits\n559\t`.claude-plugin/marketplace.json` (its `plugins[0].version`), parse-check\n560\tthat file too:\n561\t\n562\t```bash\n563\tnode -e 'JSON.parse(require(\"fs\").readFileSync(\".claude-plugin/marketplace.json\",\"utf8\"))'\n564\t```\n565\t\n566\t`node --check .opencode/plugins/entire.js` is not part of this PR because\n567\tthe shim at `.opencode/plugins/entire.js` is unchanged — it already\n568\tauto-registers the entire `skills/` directory rather than enumerating\n569\tskills, so `getting-started/SKILL.md` is picked up without any plugin code\n570\tedit. Updating `CONTRIBUTING.md`'s parse list to also cover\n571\t`.claude-plugin/marketplace.json` is intentionally out of scope for this PR\n572\t(it is a separate hygiene fix, not a precondition for shipping the new\n573\tskill).\n574\t\n575\tManual validation, performed before marking the PR ready for review:\n576\t\n577\t1. In a fresh test repo with `entire` not yet enabled, invoke the skill and\n578\t   confirm it lands on the **Setup tour** branch.\n579\t2. In a repo where `entire enable` has been run but no agents are\n580\t   installed, invoke the skill and confirm it lands on the **Agent install**\n581\t   branch.\n582\t3. In an enabled repo with an installed agent but no captured history yet,\n583\t   invoke the skill and confirm it lands on the **First-capture tour**\n584\t   branch instead of pretending there is a demo to run.\n585\t4. In `~/Projects/skills` on the current `learn-entire-cli` branch, invoke\n586\t   the skill and confirm it still lands on the **Workflow tour** branch\n587\t   even though `entire checkpoint list --no-pager` says there are no\n588\t   checkpoints on the current branch. The deciding evidence should be\n589\t   `entire dispatch --local --all-branches --since 30d`, which already\n590\t   returns recent history for this repo.\n591\t5. In a logged-in repo with indexed history and a GitHub `origin`, invoke\n592\t   the skill and confirm the demo path prefers\n593\t   `entire checkpoint search \"<current-repo-basename>\" --repo <owner/name> --json --limit 3`.\n594\t   In a logged-in repo without indexed remote results (or without a usable\n595\t   GitHub `origin`), confirm the skill falls back to local checkpoint /\n596\t   dispatch output instead of surfacing an empty search result. In a\n597\t   logged-out repo, confirm the skill stays useful via local-only commands\n598\t   and merely suggests `entire login` for cloud search.\n599\t6. Re-invoke the skill mid-conversation and confirm the response header is\n600\t   not re-printed on follow-up turns within the same invocation.\n601\t7. **Discovery (live-help) validation.** With the currently installed CLI\n602\t   (`entire 0.6.0`), invoke the skill and confirm the rendered tour:\n603\t   - lists every name in `entire --help`'s `Available Commands` block under\n604\t     either a workflow goal or \"Other commands available in your CLI\",\n605\t   - lists no command name that is not in that block (notably: it does not\n606\t     promote the hidden `entire search` alias above `entire checkpoint\n607\t     search`),\n608\t   - promotes explicit subcommand paths discovered from top-level help\n609\t     (notably `entire checkpoint search`, `entire checkpoint explain`,\n610\t     `entire session current`, and `entire agent add`) rather than only\n611\t     showing their parent groups,\n612\t   - labels `entire checkpoint search` with `(login required)` because its\n613\t     leaf help text explicitly says authentication is required even though\n614\t     `entire checkpoint --help` does not