ed workflow pattern, recommend a source set, and ask the user to confirm before expanding transcripts.\n29\t5. Do not write, install, or overwrite a skill file unless the user explicitly approves the destination. By default, present the `SKILL.md` draft in the response.\n30\t6. Do not include secrets, private credentials, raw logs, or unnecessary transcript detail in the generated skill.\n31\t\n32\t## Workflow\n33\t\n34\t### 1. Clarify The Skill Target\n35\t\n36\tIf the user gives a clear target, continue. Examples:\n37\t\n38\t- \"turn my blog publishing workflow into a skill\"\n39\t- \"make a skill from session 019...\"\n40\t- \"I keep doing release note drafting; make that reusable\"\n41\t\n42\tIf the target is vague, ask:\n43\t\n44\t```text\n45\tWhat should this skill help you do repeatedly?\n46\t```\n47\t\n48\tIf the user wants a specific skill name, use it. Otherwise infer a short hyphen-case name from the target, then confirm it before writing files.\n49\t\n50\t### 2. Infer The Repeated Pattern\n51\t\n52\tIf the user gives a checkpoint ID, skip to checkpoint expansion.\n53\t\n54\tIf the user gives a session ID, read the matching session metadata from:\n55\t\n56\t```text\n57\t.git/entire-sessions/<session-id>.json\n58\t```\n59\t\n60\tIf the user describes a repeated workflow but does not give a session or checkpoint, search Entire history with terms from the target:\n61\t\n62\t```bash\n63\tentire search \"<workflow terms>\" --json\n64\t```\n65\t\n66\tUse repo, branch, author, or date filters when the user provides them:\n67\t\n68\t```bash\n69\tentire search \"<workflow terms>\" --json --repo owner/name --branch branch-name --author \"Name\" --date month\n70\t```\n71\t\n72\tInterpret search results carefully:\n73\t\n74\t- If `entire search` returns valid JSON with `\"total\": 0` or an empty `results` array, do **not** call it an authentication failure. Say no indexed matches were found, then fall back to local session metadata.\n75\t- Only say authentication is required if the command output explicitly says authentication, login, or credentials are required.\n76\t- If search fails for any other reason, report the short error and fall back to local session metadata when available.\n77\t\n78\tWhen falling back locally, inspect `.git/entire-sessions/*.json` and match against `last_prompt`, `description`, `files_touched`, `started_at`, `last_interaction_time`, `agent_type`, and the user's workflow terms.\n79\t\n80\tReview the top results and infer the repeated workflow pattern before showing raw session choices. Lead with the pattern, not the IDs.\n81\t\n82\tPresent:\n83\t\n84\t- the repeated workflow you think the user wants to capture\n85\t- the strongest source set you recommend using\n86\t- what each source contributes in plain language, such as \"core workflow\", \"image handling\", \"validation\", or \"copy-editing pattern\"\n87\t- any sessions you plan to ignore because they look metadata-only, duplicate, or one-off\n88\t\n89\tKeep session IDs and checkpoint IDs as supporting details, not the main decision surface. Ask the user to confirm the pattern and source set before expanding detailed transcripts.\n90\t\n91\tExample:\n92\t\n93\t```text\n94\tI found a repeated workflow: publishing blog posts in entire.io from drafts, using repo-specific front matter, slugged asset folders, user-provided images, and website checks.\n95\t\n96\tI recommend using the strongest matching sessions as source material:\n97\t- core workflow: <session-id>\n98\t- image handling: <session-id>\n99\t- validation mechanics: <session-id>\n100\t\n101\tI will ignore metadata-only or one-off edit sessions unless you want them included. Should I continue with this source set?\n102\t```\n103\t\n104\t### 3. Read Source Material\n105\t\n106\tFor a checkpoint, run:\n107\t\n108\t```bash\n109\tentire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --full --no-pager\n110\t```\n111\t\n112\tIf full output fails and the user wants more detail, fall back to:\n113\t\n114\t``