hat was never answered, you MUST ask the user that question before proceeding.)\n24\t4. **Do NOT summarize the session as having \"0 turns\" or \"no progress\"** without first reading the actual transcript file. The `entire` CLI metadata often undercounts — the transcript is the source of truth.\n25\t5. **Skip your own session.** Your agent (e.g. Claude Code) also has a session in `.git/entire-sessions/`. Exclude any session whose `agent_type` matches your own agent type from the results.\n26\t\n27\t## Flow: Active / current session handoff\n28\t\n29\tWhen the user says \"current\", \"active\", or just \"hand off this session\":\n30\t\n31\t### Step 1: Run `entire status`\n32\t\n33\t```\n34\tentire status\n35\t```\n36\t\n37\tThis returns the active session ID. If the user mentioned an agent name (e.g. \"codex\"), look for that agent's session in the output.\n38\t\n39\t### Step 2: Find the transcript path\n40\t\n41\tRead the session file at `.git/entire-sessions/<session-id>.json` using the Read tool:\n42\t\n43\t```\n44\tRead: .git/entire-sessions/<session-id>.json\n45\t```\n46\t\n47\tThe file looks like this:\n48\t```json\n49\t{\n50\t  \"session_id\": \"019d730f-e099-7910-a946-b5b20e2cfafc\",\n51\t  \"agent_type\": \"Codex\",\n52\t  \"phase\": \"active\",\n53\t  \"started_at\": \"2026-04-09T09:25:21.725231-07:00\",\n54\t  \"last_interaction_time\": \"2026-04-09T09:25:21.725657-07:00\",\n55\t  \"transcript_path\": \"/Users/alisha/.codex/sessions/2026/04/09/rollout-....jsonl\",\n56\t  \"last_prompt\": \"create solitaire game\"\n57\t}\n58\t```\n59\t\n60\tExtract the `transcript_path` field. This is the path to the full conversation transcript.\n61\t\n62\t**Fallback:** If `entire status` doesn't give you a session ID, or the session JSON doesn't exist, use the Glob tool to find all `.git/entire-sessions/*.json` files, read them, and pick the most recent one (by `last_interaction_time` or `started_at`). Filter by agent name if the user specified one. Always exclude sessions matching your own agent type.\n63\t\n64\t### Step 3: Extract and summarize the transcript\n65\t\n66\t**Phase A — Extract raw transcript** (do NOT show this to the user):\n67\t\n68\t```bash\n69\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' <transcript_path> | cut -c1-2000\n70\t```\n71\t\n72\tIf the output exceeds ~500 lines, read the **last 100 lines** (final state) and **first 20 lines** (original task):\n73\t\n74\t```bash\n75\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' <transcript_path> | tail -100 | cut -c1-2000\n76\tgrep -E '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' <transcript_path> | head -20 | cut -c1-2000\n77\t```\n78\t\n79\t**Phase B — Produce a compaction summary.** Internally process the extracted transcript and produce a structured summary with these sections:\n80\t\n81\t1. **Task Overview** — The user's core request, success criteria, and any stated constraints or clarifications.\n82\t2. **Current State** — Completed work: files created/modified, key decisions made, artifacts produced.\n83\t3. **Important Discoveries** — Technical constraints uncovered, rationale behind decisions, errors hit and their resolutions, failed approaches and why they failed.\n84\t4. **Next Steps** — Specific remaining actions, blockers, and priority ordering.\n85\t5. **Context to Preserve** — User preferences, domain-specific details, and commitments made during the session.\n86\t6. **Unanswered Question** (only if applicable) — If the previous agent's last message asked the user a question or presented options that were never answered, capture it here exactly as asked.\n87\t\n88\tBe concise but complete — err on the side of including information that would prevent duplicate work or repeated mistakes.\n89\t\n90\t### Step 4: Present summary, then continue\n91\t\n92\tShow the compaction summary from Phase B to the user.\n93\t\n94\t**Critical rule — unanswered questions go to the user, not you.** If section 6 (Unanswered Question) exists, present that question to the user and wait for their answer. Do NOT answer it yourself or pick a default. The user is the decision-maker.\n95\t\n96\tIf there is no unanswered question, **immediately pick up the work** — start planning, coding, or doing whatever the next step is. Do not ask permission.\n97\t\n98\t## Flow: Checkpoint handoff (user gives a checkpoint ID)\n99\t\n100\t1. Run `entire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --full --no-pager`\n101\t2. If `--full` fails, fall back to `entire explain --checkpoint <checkpoint-id> --raw-transcript --no-pager`\n102\t3. Extract conversation content from ALL session transcripts (do NOT show raw output to the user):\n103\t\n104\t```bash\n105\tgrep -rE '\"type\":\"(message|function_call|user|assistant)\"' <transcript_dir_or_files> | cut -c1-2000\n106\t```\n107\t\n108\tFor large checkpoints with many sessions, focus on the last 100 lines per transcript to understand final state, and the first 20 lines for the original task.\n109\t\n110\t4. Produce and present a compaction summary using the same 5-section format from Step 3 Phase B above, then continue.\n111\t\n112\tResolve checkpoint repos in order: explicit override → local `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch → `.entire/settings.json` `checkpoint_remote` → nearby local clone.\n113\t\n114\t## Flow: No specific request (bare invocation)\n115\t\n116\tUse the Glob tool to find `.git/entire-sessions/*.json`. Read each file, exclude your own agent type, pick the most recent by `last_interaction_time`. Read the transcript at `transcript_path`. Summarize and continue.\n117\t\n118\t## Agent name filtering\n119\t\n120\tWords like \"codex\", \"claude\", \"kiro\", \"gemini\" in the user's request are **filters** for session selection. Match them case-insensitively against the `agent_type` field (fall back to `agent` field). Never invoke another agent's CLI.\n121\t"}]},"uuid":"47439d6e-c879-436f-aba9-e34b3078230b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T17:09:17.880Z","toolUseResult":{"type":