\n\nUse this table. Names on the left are the discovered CLI command paths;\nnames on the right are the workflow labels in the rendered tour:\n\n| If the CLI exposes…                                                                       | the skill places it under goal…       |\n| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |\n| `enable`, `disable`, `agent add`, `agent list`, `login`, `logout`, `auth`, `configure`    | Set up                                |\n| `status`, `session current`, `session list`, `session info`, `activity`                   | See what's going on                   |\n| `checkpoint search`                                                                       | Find prior work                       |\n| `checkpoint explain`, `checkpoint list`                                                   | Understand a change                   |\n| `checkpoint rewind`, `clean`                                                              | Undo / recover                        |\n| `dispatch`                                                                                | Summarize / share                     |\n| `doctor`                                                                                  | Troubleshoot                          |\n| anything else (including unknown names from a future release)                             | Other commands available in your CLI  |\n\nIf a goal has no matching command path in this CLI version, omit that\ngoal from the rendered tour. If a discovered command does not match any\ngoal, list it under \"Other commands available in your CLI\" with its\nshort description verbatim and no extra wording.\n\nPrefer canonical command spellings advertised in `entire --help`. If the\ntop-level help promotes `entire checkpoint search`, render that form even\nthough `entire search` exists today as a hidden alias. If a future CLI\nrelease promotes `search` to a top-level command (it would then appear in\n`Available Commands`), discovery picks that up and the rendered line uses\nthe shorter form on its own.\n\n### 4. Setup tour branch\n\nTell the user, in 5–8 lines:\n\n- what `entire enable` does — turns on session capture and checkpointing in\n  this repo,\n- to run it now: `entire enable`,\n- to log in if they want cloud search: `entire login`,\n- that they will be asked which agent to install hooks for, and the next\n  step is `entire agent add <agent-name>`,\n- then to re-invoke this skill so the tour can continue with real state.\n\nDo not run `entire enable` for them. Confirm each command name (`enable`,\n`login`, `agent add`) against the discovery output before printing it; if\nany one of them is missing from the live `entire --help` (e.g. on a\nstripped-down distribution), drop that line rather than print a dead\ninstruction.\n\n### 5. Agent install branch\n\nDetect the user's agent from environment when possible (`CLAUDE_CODE`,\n`CODEX_*`, `CURSOR_*`, `OPENCODE_*`, etc.); fall back to asking. Tell the\nuser:\n\n- to run `entire agent add <agent-name>` and that this installs hooks that\n  capture sessions and create checkpoints on commit,\n- that `entire agent list` shows what is supported.\n\nIf `agent` and its `add` / `list` subcommands are missing from the\ndiscovered surface, fall back to: \"Run `entire help` to see how to install\nagent hooks in your version.\"\n\n### 6. First-capture tour branch\n\nEntire is enabled and a supported agent is installed, but there is not\nenough captured history yet to demo the workflows concretely. Tell the\nuser that checkpoints are created automatically when their agent runs\nand commits, and that to see the system end-to-end they should:\n\n- run a small task with their agent (any task, even \"say hello in a\n  comment\"),\n- commit the change,\n- optionally run `entire login` if they want cloud search as part of the\n  tour,\n- come back and re-invoke this skill — there will be captured history to\n  demo.\n\nDo not fabricate a checkpoint or run a placeholder task on the user's\nbehalf.\n\n### 7. Workflow tour branch (the main path)\n\nRender the goals → command recipe. Build the lines from the discovery\noutput: any goal whose required command path is absent is dropped, any\ncommand path with `requiresLogin` true gets a `(login required)` suffix,\nand any command with `isExperimental` true gets an `(experimental)`\nsuffix. Mention each focused skill at most once, only on the line where\nthe workflow already exists in the CLI.\n\n```text\nHere is what your installed Entire CLI can do (entire <CLI version>):\n\n- Set up                  →  entire enable / entire agent add <name> / entire login\n- See what's going on     →  entire status / entire session current / entire session list / entire activity\n- Find prior work         →  entire checkpoint search \"<query>\" (login required)      (deeper: /search)\n- Understand a change     →  entire checkpoint explain <id|sha>                       (deeper: /explain, /what-happened)\n- Undo / recover          →  entire checkpoint rewind  /  entire clean\n- Summarize / share       →  entire dispatch --since 7d                               (deeper: /session-handoff)\n- Troubleshoot            →  entire doctor\n\nOther commands available in your CLI:\n- <name>: <short description verbatim from `entire --help`>\n- ...\n```\n\nThen **demo exactly one** concrete Entire result. Try the candidates in\nthis order; only attempt a candidate whose command appeared in the\ndiscovery output:\n\n1. **Repo-scoped remote search.** If `entire auth status` says the user\n   is logged in **and** `git config --get remote.origin.url` resolves to\n   a GitHub repo slug:\n\n   ```bash\n   entire checkpoint search \"<current-repo-basename>\" --repo <owner/name> --json --limit 3\n   ```\n\n   If that search returns at least one hit, summarize the top hit as the\n   demo and point out that `/search` is the skill for deeper use. If it\n   returns zero hits, do **not** show an empty result — fall through to\n   the local checkpoint / dispatch demo so the tour still ends with\n   evidence from this repo.\n\n2. **Newest local checkpoint.** Otherwise, if `entire checkpoint list\n   --no-pager` shows at least one checkpoint on the current branch:\n\n   ```bash\n   entire checkpoint explain <checkpoint-id> --short --no-pager\n   ```\n\n   Summarize that checkpoint as the demo and note that `/explain` and\n   `/what-happened` drill into the same captured history more precisely.\n\n3. **Local cross-branch summary.** Otherwise:\n\n   ```bash\n   entire dispatch --local --all-branches --since 30d\n   ```\n\n   Summarize one recent thread of work and frame it as \"this is the\n   captured history the deeper workflows search and explain.\"\n\nEnd with one short line pointing at `https://docs.entire.io/cli` for\ndeeper docs and noting that `/search`, `/explain`, `/what-happened`,\n`/session-handoff`, and `/session-to-skill` drill into the workflows\nabove when the user wants more than the CLI recipes.\n\n## Failure Modes\n\nDistinguish and report each of these states explicitly:\n\n- `entire` not installed → \"The Entire CLI is required but not installed.\n  Install it from https://docs.entire.io/cli/install and try again.\" No\n  header.\n- Current directory is not a git repo → \"Entire works inside a git\n  repository. Run `git init` first or `cd` into one, then re-invoke this\n  skill.\" No header.\n- `entire status` works but says disabled → enter the Setup tour branch.\n  This is success — apply the header.\n- `entire login` required for cloud search → mention it in the tour but\n  do not block local-only tours on it. `status`, `session current`,\n  `checkpoint list`, and `dispatch --local` still give the user value\n  without logging in.\n- `entire --help` runs but the `Available Commands:` block parses empty\n  → fail open as described in Workflow step 2: print goal label